#1 pT3, N1, M1, completely resected adenocarcinoma of the distal sigmoid
This disease was completely resected by Dr. Robinson on February 4, 2010.  Although therapy for rectal cancer was discussed, it apparently was decided not to give chemoradiation therapy because of known systemic involvement.  Dr. Sullivan has tolerated the chemotherapy with irinotecan only poorly, likely because of a polymorphism in the UGT1A1 gene.  Also, Avastin had to be stopped after several doses because of deteriorating renal function.  Dr. Sullivan has discussed with his oncologist to continue the 5-FU/leucovorin for another 18 months.  I discussed with him that after completion of 12 cycles of adjuvant therapy, there is no evidence that further chemotherapy would be of any benefit nor is it defined for how long chemotherapy should be continued.  On the other hand, In Dr. Sullivan's case, only a small part of the planned chemotherapy was given and he himself is quite conflicted whether he should continue with the 5-FU/leucovorin only.  He understands that there is currently no data that points in either direction based on evidence.  We have discussed again that since his tumor is KRAS wild-type, he would be eligible for treatment with cetuximab, should a recurrence happen.  He briefly asked whether BRAF testing would be indicated, and I explained that BRAF mutations have no predictive value with regard to cetuximab sensitivity.
#2 Subtle irregularity in the bile ducts
This is a finding seen on the most recent MRI of the abdomen.  I discussed this finding with Dr. Glen Garner from Radiology.  He stated that this is only seen on one series and that he therefore would not be particularly concerned.  The main reason he had mentioned this was because of a questionable history of inflammatory bowel disease and, in the setting, Dr. Sullivan might have an increased risk for sclerosing cholangitis.  Although initially the macroscopic findings during colonoscopy and CT scanning had indicated the possibility of inflammatory bowel disease, the pathology report from the colectomy does not describe any evidence for this.  Therefore we felt that it is reasonable to follow-up in three-months with a repeat MRI integrating an MRCP into this examination.  Dr. Burns assessment greatly reassured Dr. Sullivan, and we will follow this up three-months from now.
#3 Congenital single kidney
This is the main reason for Dr. Arana impaired renal function.  Another contributing factor is diabetes.  He will therefore not be able to receive any more CT scans that require contrast.
I discussed with Dr. Sullivan that he should follow-up in three-months with a repeat MRI.  At that time, I will see him back in my clinic and discuss further approach to therapy.  We again discussed at length that continuing therapy in the face of no evidence of disease is not a proven approach.  It is currently being studied in clinical trials.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

