[start section id="20103"]

Dr. Sullivan is a 48-year-old obstetrician from Loretto, Minnesota, who has had a pT3, N1, M1 adenocarcinoma 11.5 cm from the anal verge, resected on February 4, 2010.  At the same time, a single liver metastasis in segment VI was resected.  I have not seen Dr. Sullivan since his surgery.  He underwent adjuvant therapy with FOLFIRI plus Avastin.  This combination was chosen because Dr. Sullivan is a surgeon himself and was anxious about peripheral neuropathy.  Unfortunately, Dr. Sullivan tolerated the irinotecan only poorly.  He has a polymorphism in the UGT1A1 gene.  His dose was therefore reduced by 50%, but he still tolerated it only poorly.  After nine cycles, the irinotecan was omitted from the regimen.  Since then, he has had two more doses of 5-FU/leucovorin only.  He will complete this for a total of 12 cycles.
Dr. Sullivan reports significant fatigue even with the 5-FU alone.  He denies diarrhea, but his main problem is a "bad taste" in the mouth as well as nasal ulcers.  He did notice a small area of numbness and tingling on the back of his left-hand about a month ago.  This has not become worse or better since then.
An MRI of the abdomen performed on August 5, 2010, did not show any evidence of recurrence of disease.  The reports describes a subtle irregularity of the common bile duct only on series 2.  A CT-scan of the chest without contrast did not reveal any abnormalities.  CBC and chemistry are within acceptable limits.  CEA is 2.0.

[end section id="20103"]

